  "prompt": "Will USB 3.1 require a different front panel header than USB 3? Also, will computer case makers implement USB-C on front panels?",
  "response": "USB 3.1 and USB 3.0 both use the same front panel header, which is the USB 3.0 header (also known as the USB 3.1 Gen 1 header). This means that motherboards that support USB 3.1 Gen 2 (the faster version of USB 3.1) do not require a different front panel header; they can use the existing USB 3.0 headers for connectivity.\n\nAs for USB-C implementation, many computer case manufacturers have started including USB-C ports on front panels to support modern devices. The inclusion of USB-C in cases depends on market demand, as well as the typical use cases for the target audience of those cases. As USB-C continues to gain popularity among devices like smartphones, tablets, and peripherals, it's likely that more cases will feature USB-C ports in the front panel. Always check the specific case specifications to confirm the availability of USB-C.",
